This compound is thus a lucky coincidence on two levels.

This matches the etymologies of "potassium" and "kalium", even though potassium is only the second most common metal found in ashes after calcium.
Calque of the Japanese 軽銀/keigin, "light silver".
Aluminium is the most common metal in rock.
Inspired by the probable etymology of the Czech word "hliník" (apparently derived from "earth/soil/clay").
Lackafi confirmed the etymology of the Czech word as being indeed derived from the word "hlína" ("soil"), on the basis of the authoritative Czech etymological dictionary by Jiří Rejzek.
Calque of the Navajo "béésh ászólí" ("light metal").
The Māori word "konukōhatu" also literally means "stone metal".

This word also allows for super nifty compounds that correspond to English words ending in -ise/-ize: mitōaqfīoq (‘to Toaqise’), joqmūafīoq (‘epitomise’)… as opposed to similar compounds ending in -(shō)tūa, which aren’t always semantically aligned.

7608.head: tẻoqdūe
7608.body: ▯ is the answer to ▯, where the second blank necessarily refers to whatever question you just asked me."tẻoqdūe" is a technically logical answer to any question whatsoever. questioner: "Why do you beat your dog?" Answerer who doesn't feel like explaining that they never did beat their dog so the question is irrelevant and answers: "tẻoqdūe." Technically this counts, by definition, as an answer to the questioner's question, and may signal the answerer does not feel the need to give a more detailed answer. "Why are you such a dork?" "tẻoqdūe."

7609.head: Tủqcā
7609.body: ▯ is the ultimate explanation for everything in set ▯. (Defaults to the ultimate cause of the universe in context.) "Why didn't you do the laundry?" "Tủqcā" (could be translated as "The physical laws plus boundary conditions of the universe." "Tủqcā" is technically an answer to pretty much any question, and a signal that perhaps you should specify what level of explanation you are looking for before asking, like "what did you do this morning instead of the laundry" instead. Can also probably be used in physics contexts.

notes.content: I should specify it's the answer to pretty much any "why" type question.
"kuıtū" would be a better compound for that, IMO.

8494.body: What satisfies property ▯ is independent of what satisfies property ▯

notes.content: In other words, there are no ordered pairs (A, B) that are forbidden from satisfying the properties (P1, P2), unless A is always forbidden from satisfying P1 or B is always forbidden from satisfying P2
Another way of saying the same thing is that the ordered pairs (A, B) that can satisfy (P1, P2) are simply the cross product of the values A that can satisfy P1 and the values B that can satisfy P2

8785.head: meq
8785.body: quantifier: the proposition in which this quantifier appears is treated as a property with a lambda slot placed exactly where this quantifier appears; the resulting property is then claimed to satisfy the first slot of the predicate introduced by this quantifier.

notes.content: ``mủıdūa meq nỏa ní`` = ``nỏa mûıdūa ja ní``.

``meq hảo`` is similar to ``hão`` but instead of delivering a proposition (lû) to the first slot of ``hao`` as is the case with the latter, it passes a property (lî) to it. Compare ``chỏq jí ní jẽaq dảqfāı`` —"I use this increasingly frequently"— with ``chỏq meq pủıjēaq ní`` —"increasingly many ones use this"—.

What can be expressed as ``gủaı meq dùq póq`` under the alternative definition #46CV57Aje can be expressed as per this very definition as ``gủaı póq ru meq hỏpā dủq``, which is three syllables more. Hopefully the additional flexibility allowed by this one definition is a sufficient compensation.

9377.head: jıoı
9377.body:
⚙ [JIOI] Tu củaqmūıbō bı lủcōetōa lú sỉemē hóa shú jıoı cúaqmūıbō shú ga, kıo dàı sa rảı bı pảqnūa há shú ga kı, ceı müıbō hóa pó cúaqmūıbō da.
Mủa ní pủq da:
• ①̉   ②́   jıoı  ③̉   (ga)  ④́  =  ③̉   ①̂  ②́   na  ①̂  ④́ .
• ①̉   jıoı  ②̉  ga  ③̉   =  ②̉  ①̂  na  ③̂ .
• ①̉   ②́   na jıoı  ③̉  ga  ④̉  ⑤́   =  ③̉   ①̂  ②́   na  ④̂  ⑤́ .
• ①̉   ②̃  jıoı  ③̉   (ga)  ④̃  =  ③̉   ②̂   ①̂  na na  ④̂  ①̂ .

11924.head: kuxāı
11924.body: 'orientation'; ▯ʼs orientation in aspect/relevant to property ▯  is described by property ▯

notes.content: Word form inspired by "kuaı". The second place relates to a scale and/or collection of beliefs or behaviors and the third place describes exactly what behaviors or beliefs the referent of the first place exhibits, or where they are on the scale

"Kủxāı súq lî củe ru cảq ja baq jủaocīao hı moq?"—"What is your political orientation" (Or "Please describe what properties best describe your beliefs/behaviors as relevant to ruling and managing societies")
This bisyllabic root is purposefully very broad and as such can be used to name sexual, gender, political, etc. orientation
This could be used for a "secret society" which can be microsocieties of their own, but is normally used for any governed subsection of human civilization that more or less shares a common culture

notes.content: Word form inspired by "kuaı". The second place relates to a scale and/or collection of beliefs or behaviors and the third place describes exactly what behaviors or beliefs the referent of the first place exhibits, or where they are on the scale  "Kủxāı hı súq lî củe ra cảq ja baq jủaocīao moq?"—"What is your political orientation" (Or "Please describe what properties best describe your beliefs/behaviors as relevant to ruling and managing societies")  This bisyllabic root is purposefully very broad and as such can be used to name sexual, gender, political, etc. orientation

notes.content: When applied to non-matrix clauses, it behaves similarly to "ceı lü" or "ceı ru lủ"; when applied to the matrix clause, the relative clause ends with the illocution marker.
